tained comparative financial data for the most recent school year.\"", "\"ST TRINIAN'S\":\"St Trinian's is a school with 700 pupils, an average class size of 15, and total costs of $3,343,000. The costs include teaching, back office, buildings maintenance, internet and computers for students, and energy.\"", "\"CHARACTERISTICS OF PUBLIC SECTOR ORGANISATIONS\":\"Public sector organisations often have a broader group of stakeholders, customers do not pay for the services they receive, they are often monopoly providers, and it is difficult to measure their output. These characteristics differentiate them from commercial organisations.\"", "\"EVALUATION OF NORTHTOWN VS ST TRINIAN'S\":\"The evaluation compares the performance of Northtown and St Trinian's using benchmark data. It calculates the cost per pupil for each category and highlights that St Trinian's has higher teaching costs due to smaller class sizes and potentially higher salaries, while Northtown has higher back office costs, suggesting inefficiency.\"", "\"NORTHTOWN\":", "\"BAR SALES REPORT\":\"The bar sales report compares total billing without distinguishing between residents and non-residents due to the high number of cash transactions.\"", "\"RESTAURANT AND BAR INVENTORY REPORT\":\"The restaurant and bar inventory report involves physical control over inventory, with head office officials attending physical counts and using these as benchmarks for subsequent movements. The report highlights significant percentage variations from preceding months to indicate pilferage and misappropriation.\"", "\"CASH AVAILABILITY REPORT\":\"The cash availability report summarizes cash takings and receipts from bar and restaurant operations, comparing them across hotels while accounting for differences in resident types.\"", "\"WAGES REPORT\":\"The wages report details the number of waged staff per week and their wages, comparing this to revenue reports to identify inefficiencies or potential fraud.\"", "\"ERROR/EXCEPTION REPORTS\":\"Error/exception reports are automatically generated by computer systems to highlight significant deviations such as hotel revenue falling below budget, cash reserves exceeding limits, or rooms being given below approved rates.\"", "\"COST ANALYSIS OF PRODUCTS A, B, AND C: TRADITIONAL VS. ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING\":\"Gadget Co produces three products (A, B, and C) and is considering switching from traditional absorption costing to activity-based costing to improve profitability. The case involves calculating the full cost per unit for each product under both costing methods and analyzing how activity-based costing can enhance profitability.\"", "\"ACTIVITY BASED COSTING\":\"Activity based costing (ABC) is a costing method that assigns overhead and indirect costs to related products and services by identifying cost drivers.\"", "\"COST POOLS\":\"Cost pools are groups of individual costs, typically by department or service center, from which cost allocations are made later.\"", "\"MAXIMIZING NET PROFIT AND THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING ANALYSIS FOR PRODUCTS A AND B\":\"Flopro makes and sells two products, A and B, each passing through the same automated production operations. The case involves analyzing the profitability and throughput accounting for these products.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}